film, including both mainstream and independent cinematic representations. The contributors draw on a variety of critical approaches to consider the spectacle of pregnancy; mother-daughter relationships; mothers as predators, narcissists, and absent victims; and the ways in which cultural anxieties are displaced and projected onto marginalized mothers in films such as Fargo; Transamerica; Gas, Food, Lodging; Ordinary People; and Scream. Ideal for women's studies or film studies classes, Motherhood Misconceived will help students contextualize current debates about motherhood as they play out in popular and independent film.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aMotherhood in motion pictures. 0aMotherhoodzUnited States. 0aSex role in motion pictures. 4aFilm, Visual Culture, and Performing Arts : Film Studies. 4aGender and Sexuality : Women's Studies. 4aSociology : Family Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Women's Studies.2bisacsh1 aAddison, Heather, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAddison, Heather, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBerger, Aimee, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChopra-Gant, Mike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCutler, Janet K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDalton, Mary M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodwin-Kelly, Mary Kate, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodwin-Kelly, Mary Kate, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHarper, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKarlyn, Kathleen Rowe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcDonald, Tamar Jeffers, econtributor.4